Hi there! I just had a few comments on your post.

First off, make sure to properly address the person you're talking to! You wouldn't just walk up to someone and launch straight into critique, would you? Of course not!

Second, do make sure you are properly following the rules of grammar. Contractions can be confusing but it helps to talk it out as if both words are present. "Where it is just the dialogue and characters WHICH ARE described" woulf be a proper sentence.

As a smaller aside: Do not use "then" for chronological order of events in an imperative statement unless you also add an explicit imperative clause like "you need to"

Third, make sure you always break up separate but complete thoughts in a sentence with commas or semicolons. That'll help you avoid those nasty run on sentences.

Fourth, make sure to be consistent when making a list. If you start a pattern (like "firstly," "secondly," etc.) then continue that pattern. Also be sure not to repeat introductory words or phrases.

Finally, dialogue does not adhere to rigid rules of construction. Use and abuse of ellipses and dashes, with or without spaces, is absolutely and demonstrably fine. What's important is that the reader understands the tone and cadence of what is being said.

Besides that? Not bad!
